450","England":"England","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England","Bury St Edmunds, Suffolk, England":"Bury St Edmunds, Suffolk, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Moody","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Irish: nickname from Middle English <i>mody</i> ‘proud, haughty, angry, fierce, bold, brave, or rash’ (Old English <i>mōdig</i>). Compare   Muddiman  . This English name has been established in Ireland since the late 13th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Woody","meanings":["English:","from Middle English <i>wode</i> ‘wood’ + <i>heie</i> ‘enclosure’ (Old English <i>wudu</i> + <i>(ge)hæg</i>). The surname may be topographic, for someone who lived by an enclosure in a wood, or habitational, for a person from a place so named, such as Woodhey Green in Faddiley (Cheshire). Also possibly from East Woodhay (Hampshire) and West Woodhay (Berkshire), apparently named with Old English <i>wīd</i> ‘wide, broad’ as the initial element, confused with early Old English <i>widu</i> ‘wood’, and so too with Old English <i>wudu</i>.","nickname from Middle English <i>wodi</i> or some other derivative of Middle English <i>wode</i> ‘frenzied, wild’ (Old English <i>wōd</i>), perhaps formed on the analogy of, for example, Middle English <i>mody</i> (see   Moody  ). Compare   Wood   2."]},{"name":"Muddiman","meanings":["English (Northamptonshire): nickname from Middle English <i>mody</i> ‘proud, haughty, angry, fierce, bold, brave, rash’ (Old English <i>mōdig</i>) + <i>man</i> ‘man’. See   Moody  ."]},{"name":"Mooty","meanings":["English: variant of   Moody  . This form of the surname is rare in Britain.","Possibly an Americanized form of German <b>Mutig</b>, a nickname meaning ‘cheerful’."]},{"name":"Moodie","meanings":["English and Scottish: variant of   Moody  ."]},{"name":"Moudy","meanings":["English (London): variant of   Moody  . This form of the surname is rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Mowdy","meanings":["English or Irish: variant of   Moody  ."]},{"name":"Mudie","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scottish Iain.","English and Scottish (Angus): variant of   Moody  ."]}]},{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":5,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705201,"age":99,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705202,"age":108,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"When Richard Moody was born about 1450, in England, his father, William Moodye, was 21 and his mother, Anne Edmond, was 19. He married Ursula Sadler. They were the parents of at least 2 sons."},"et":{"about 1450–":"umbes 1450–Surnud","1450–Male":"1450–Surnud","1450–1528":"1450–1528","1475–1567":"1475–1567","1430–1480":"1430–1480","1432–1477":"1432–1477","1450":"1450","1480":"1480","1558":"1558","1567":"1567","1455":"1455","1477":"1477","about 1449":"umbes 1449","1432":"1432","1475":"1475","1430":"1430","1528":"1528","1549":"1549","about 1450":"umbes 1450","England":"England","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England","Bury St Edmunds, Suffolk, England":"Bury St Edmunds, Suffolk, England"},"fi":{"about 1450–":"noin 1450–Kuollut","1450–Male":"1450–Kuollut